properties.description: 25 homes designed with the Older Women’s Co-Housing group using PTE’s ‘fabric first’ approach which maximises the benefits of orientation, air-tightness, insulation and following the co-housing model. www.youtube.com/watch?v=9q25nbEl8rg
properties.name: New Ground (online only)

properties.description: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre, at Hornchurch Country Park, the Former RAF Hornchurch Airfield.
properties.name: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre

properties.description: Built in a Renaissance style with high level Diocletian windows and a prominent grand cupola. In 2016 a new Fly Tower opened followed by remodelling of the auditorium in 2018 and the creation of a new basement space opening in the Autumn.
properties.name: Shaftesbury Theatre

properties.description: The building was designed by the internationally acclaimed architects David Chipperfield Architects and is now occupied by Gustafson Porter + Bowman. The areas are arranged spaciously with an abundance of natural light throughout.
properties.name: Gustafson Porter + Bowman

properties.description: Beautiful mausoleum in former Royal Navy cemetery, restored 1999 by the University of Greenwich. Many interesting plaques and grave stones.
properties.name: Devonport Mausoleum

properties.description: The former studio home of the sculptor Dora Gordine and her husband the Hon. Richard Hare, a scholar of Russian art and literature. 1930s house over four floors including a flat roof terrace and views of Richmond Park.
properties.name: Dorich House Museum

properties.description: Architecturally distinguished and well-preserved, brick-built, Elizabethan Grade I listed manor house. Contains 17C wall-paintings, wood panelling, a charming walled garden and a fine Tudor turret. Many original features have been restored.
properties.name: Eastbury Manor House

properties.description:
Listed Arts and Crafts freestyle building with plain interior and many charming original features, sympathetically modernised in 1991. Entrance via listed gateway.
NOTE Please wear facemasks.
properties.name: Hampstead Friends Meeting House

properties.description: Delightful brick and tile building inspired by the famous 1688 Meeting House at Jordans in Buckinghamshire. A simple building in a tranquil setting, reflecting the Quakers' beliefs.
properties.name: Golders Green Quaker Meeting House

properties.description: Grade I listed Georgian garden building. Tribute to Shakespeare built in the Ionic style by actor David Garrick. Arcadian Thames-side setting in restored 18C gardens thought to be by Capability Brown.
properties.name: Garrick's Temple to Shakespeare, Hampton

properties.description: Guided walks of 'the most nearly perfect example of the 20C Garden Suburb' (Pevsner), designed by Unwin & Parker, Lutyens, Bunney, Baillie Scott and others. Informally laid out terraces and picturesque Arts and Crafts vernacular cottages.
properties.name: Hampstead Garden Suburb Artisans' Quarter Walk

properties.description: Fine stuccoed building overlooking Pond Square, and home to Institution since 1840. Formed from 1790 coach house, stables and yard, with final additions c1880. Guided tours will be available.
properties.name: Highgate Literary & Scientific Institution

properties.description: A sumptuous feast of Victorian stained glass & bold sacred sculpture in what Sir John Betjeman called the 'cathedral of the Arts and Crafts movement.' Work by William Morris, Edward Burne-Jones, William Blake Richamind & Christopher Whall.
properties.name: Holy Trinity Church Sloane Square

properties.description: Grade II* listed tower with restored chapel remaining from Medieval parish church. Tour includes crypt, ringing chamber & main roof with excellent extensive views in all directions. Organised by Friends of Hornsey Church Tower.
properties.name: Tower and Churchyard of St Mary's Hornsey

properties.description: The home of Emery Walker, printer, antiquary and mentor to William Morris. A unique Arts and Crafts domestic interior.
properties.name: Emery Walker's House

properties.description: The World’s largest tidal mill. 5-storey, timber-framed, brick-clad timber watermill with four waterwheels, originally built 1776 to mill grain for distillery trade. Operational until 1940. On historic 3 Mills Site, Clock Mill adjacent.
properties.name: House Mill

properties.description: 1939 Art Deco Grade II listed building refurbished in 1950, then restructured and modernised in 2014. Contains an authentically classic cinema, private salons and multimedia library.
properties.name: Institut français du Royaume-Uni

properties.description: Grade I listed 1934 residential block of flats in Hampstead, designed by the Canadian modernist architect Wells Coates for clients Jack and Molly Pritchard. English Heritage blue plaque for Bauhaus masters Gropius, Breuer and Moholy-Nagy.
properties.name: Isokon Building (Lawn Road Flats)

properties.description:
A Grade II* listed church dating from 13th century with some interesting features
Adjacent to a 16th century Gate House
properties.name: St Martin's Parish Church, West Drayton

properties.description: Wren-designed building completed under the direction of Hawksmoor and Vanbrugh, 1698-1712. Original wood panelling, refurbished by Dannatt Johnson in 2001 for University of Greenwich.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - King William Court

properties.description: Landmark Edwardian Baroque style town hall  in red brick and Portland stone landmark tower.  Interior has marble staircase and ornate council chamber.  Atrium, reception and courtyard spaces created in 2018. Grade II listed.
properties.name: Lambeth Town Hall

properties.description: Victorian church of cathedral proportions, built in the French Gothic style, through public subscription. Grade II* listed. Restored 1993, now functioning as a community arts centre.
properties.name: Landmark Arts Centre

properties.description: Lincoln’s Inn has been an association of barristers for over 600 years. An 11-acre site combining gardens with mediaeval, Victorian, Georgian, and modern buildings, including banqueting halls, a law library, a chapel, and teaching space.
properties.name: Lincoln's Inn

properties.description:
A masterpiece of Victorian engineering, Markfield Beam Engine provided a vital public health facility from 1855-1964. 

On 17 & 18 Sept the 1888 beam engine will be steaming as follows:
12.30 - 1.15pm 
2.00 - 2.45pm 
3.30 - 4.15pm
properties.name: Markfield Beam Engine and House

properties.description: Grade I listed, late Georgian sugar warehouse now housing the Museum of London Docklands. Sensitively restored, the new multimedia displays coexist with the massive timber and brick structures of the original building.
properties.name: Museum of London Docklands

properties.description: Early Tudor Palace with Georgian reception rooms, Victorian Chapel, 13 acres of botanic gardens and walled garden.
properties.name: Fulham Palace

properties.description: Magnificent Victorian cemetery with Gothic chapel & restored & ruined lodge. One of London's wildest cemeteries. Part restored with the help of a lottery grant. 52 acres of woodland, with bats, owls, foxes & squirrels. Grade II*  landscape.
properties.name: Nunhead Cemetery

properties.description: Sir Christopher Wren's riverside masterpiece in Greenwich, built as the Royal Hospital for Seamen and begun in 1696.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College

properties.description: Designed by Sir John Soane as a family home and country residence. Following a three-year conservation project,  Pitzhanger has been returned to Soane’s innovative original design and re-opened to the public in March 2019.
properties.name: Pitzhanger Manor & Gallery

properties.description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm. Closed Mon 19 September.
Guided tours 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays, see below.
Home of the City of London's art collection, & remains of London's Roman Amphitheatre
properties.name: UPDATED: Guildhall Art Gallery

properties.description: Wren and Hawksmoor building, completed 1749 when Thomas Ripley built the pavilions facing the river. Highlights include council boardroom, grand staircase and restored Portland stonework. Refurbished in 2000 for University of Greenwich.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Anne Court

properties.description: Tudor timber-framed hunt standing/grandstand (1543),  Henry VIII Tudor food display. Gateway to 6,000 acres ancient Epping Forest, once royal hunting ground, protected since 1878 by City of London, Grade II*.  Epping Forest visitor Centre.
properties.name: Queen Elizabeth's Hunting Lodge

properties.description: Last major building on the site (1751). Original layout, timber panelling, barrel vaulting and Portland stone. Refurbished in 2000 by Dannatt Johnson for University of Greenwich.
properties.name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Mary Court

properties.description: A very good example of Georgian/Adam architecture. Restoration 2012 of Great Room (James Barry paintings), Benjamin Franklin room. 2019, restoration and installation of 1754-2018 mural in the new Long Gallery.
properties.name: RSA (Royal Society for the encouragement of Arts, Manufactures and Commerce)

properties.description: Unique example of Expressionist architecture in London with sculptural staircase based on organic plant forms. Grade II listed. New cafe area and renovations in 2008. Refurbishment of theatre and foyer 2020.
properties.name: Rudolf Steiner House

properties.description: A close of 13 self-built houses. Each is unique, built using method developed by Walter Segal, who led the project in the 1980s. Houses have been extended and renovated. Sustainable features including solar electric, water & space heating.
properties.name: Walter Segal Self-build Houses

properties.description: Once one of the grandest civic buildings in London and now a great arts venue, the Grade II listed Shoreditch Town Hall boasts many spaces, from the Victorian grandeur of the Assembly Hall to the intimate warren of untouched basement rooms.
properties.name: Shoreditch Town Hall

properties.description: Europe’s first traditional Hindu temple is a masterpiece of exquisite Indian craftsmanship. Using 5,000 tonnes of Italian and Indian marble and the finest Bulgarian limestone, it was hand-carved in India before being assembled in London.
properties.name: BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir

properties.description: Grade II listed 1881 former fire station with prominent watch tower and original fire doors.
properties.name: South London Theatre

properties.description: Grade I listed, remaining tower of medieval parish church, with working late 16C clock. New exhibition of Hackney's history. Extensive views from roof. (Organised by Hackney Historic Buildings Trust).
properties.name: St Augustine's Tower

properties.description: Grade I listed church dating from 1086, representing the architectural styles of many centuries, including Norman font and carved cats heads around Norman south doorway arch, Easter sepulchre and ancient yew tree in churchyard.
properties.name: St Peter & St Paul Harlington

properties.description: Wren's own and 'finest City Church'.  Fantastic architecture with different shapes,  twelve Corinthian columns and covered by huge dome - first of its type. Central stone altar by Henry Moore installed in 1987. Birthplace of the Samaritans.
properties.name: The City Churches: St Stephen Walbrook

properties.description: Ground breaking post-war reinforced concrete building with cavernous interior. Sweeping roof structure with a clear single span of 194 feet, the lack of internal columns making best use of space. Opening by kind permission of Go-Ahead.
properties.name: Stockwell Bus Garage

properties.description: Influential early Gothic revival building restored to its dramatic original glory, recreating Walpole's original intention for his own home.
properties.name: Strawberry Hill House & Garden

properties.description: Grade II* listed, originally the Merchant Seaman's Orphan Asylum, bought by the synagogue in 1995 and restored with Lottery Fund grant. Timber work and windows from a synagogue which was inside the Tottenham Home for Incurables.
properties.name: Sukkat Shalom Reform Synagogue

properties.description: 6-storey building featuring a Western exterior and traditional Islamic interior, modelled on the Blue Mosque in Istanbul. Has dome and minaret tower.
properties.name: Suleymaniye Mosque

properties.description: Temple Bar is a 350 year old gateway to the City of London, designed by Sir Christopher Wren. It formerly stood in Fleet Street, and was the last surviving gateway to the City of London.
properties.name: Temple Bar

properties.description: 1713 terraced house with 1914 hall at rear. Notable renovated Arts and Crafts interior. Newly refurbished glass vaulted courtyard. Portraits of Guild Masters since 1884.
properties.name: Table Top Museums at the Art Workers' Guild

properties.description:
"ARGENTINA AT THE LONDON DESIGN FESTIVAL 2022" 
During Open House Festival people will have the unique opportunity to visit and explore the historic mansion host to the exhibition “Creative experience- From Argentina to the world”
properties.name: Argentine Ambassador's Residence

properties.description: Part of an international family of Ismaili Centres, a religious, cultural and social space for the Shia Imami Ismaili Muslims. The serenity of the entrance fountain to the roof garden reflects Muslim traditions in architecture and design
properties.name: The Ismaili Centre

properties.description:
Grade II listed building from 1889 with diverse historical functions - now functioning as Theatre venue and dance studios.
A more recent remodelling and additional dance studios has made the complex a bright and contemporary venue.
properties.name: The Place

properties.description: The Barbican Centre is a world-class arts, learning and conference centre set in the Grade II listed Barbican Estate – one of London’s best examples of Brutalist architecture.
properties.name: Barbican Centre

properties.description: Outdoor pool 100x33 yards. One million gallons of unheated water. Iconic outdoor cubicle doors, fountain and café added in the 1930s, with Art Deco style entrance in 2001. Sports hall pavilion added in 2016.
properties.name: Tooting Bec Lido

properties.description: One of the first garden suburbs in the world, 2-storey terraced cottages retaining decorative architectural features. LCC created 'housing of the working classes' role for architects' department under Riley, member of the Art Workers guild.
properties.name: Self-guided Tower Gardens Garden Suburb Walk

properties.description: The world's founding university settlement. Built to provide educational & social spaces for East Londoners. Neo-Tudor Grade II listed building with notable room decorated by Arts & Crafts designer CR Ashbee. Restoration completed in 2018.
properties.name: Toynbee Hall

properties.description: A Grade I and II*  treasure that’s home to an inclusive church, an award winning venue, a unique organ and The Margins Project for those in crisis in London. Book organ workshop and performance https://unionchapel.org.uk/venue/whats-on
properties.name: Union Chapel

properties.description: A unique II* listed Italianate church by John Dando Sedding with attached Campanile and Institute Building. Of particular significance in the church is the imposing baldacchino over the High Altar, which dominates the east end.
properties.name: The Church of Our Most Holy Redeemer

properties.description: Grade I listed Georgian house, the only surviving home of Benjamin Franklin, retaining many original features including central staircase, lathing, 18th Century panelling, stoves, windows, fittings and beams.
properties.name: Benjamin Franklin House

properties.description: Rare example of a hollow post mill (1817). Grade II* listed, it now contains a museum depicting the history and development of windmills in Britain. Many working models, windmill machinery, equipment and tools.
properties.name: Wimbledon Windmill

properties.description: Grade I listed pioneering brick polychromy. Designed with early Christian, Italian, Ottoman, Alhambran, Mamluk, Sevillean and Ancient Egyptian influences with fine mosaics and stained glass by Crane, Bentley. Lee and Hayward.
properties.name: Christ Church, Streatham

properties.description: Magnificent English Baroque church, Grade I listed, gutted by fire in 1941 and restored by Sir Albert Richardson to original design. Many original features. Burial site of Thomas Tallis, organist/choirmaster (1505-85).
properties.name: St Alfege Church, Greenwich

properties.description: Meticulous 1930s rebuilding (complete with original furnishings) of an 1840s Marylebone church. Grade I listed. Contains works by Pugin, Burges, Street, Pearson and Butterfield.
properties.name: St Andrew's Kingsbury (new church)

properties.description: Grade I listed early medieval parish church (from 952 before Tower of London) in spacious churchyard. Fine interior: Anglo-Saxon Rood, Norman font, 'squint', fine memorials incl founders of Trinity House, 1950s glass. Bells of Stepney.
properties.name: St Dunstan and All Saints Church

properties.description:
Possibly the last stone-vaulted building built in London – of soaring nobility embellished with carvings and fittings of exceptional quality.
Recently cleaned and restored by Opus Conservation, Humphries & Jones and others
properties.name: St John the Baptist Holland Road

properties.description: Eccentric Edwardian church, Grade I listed. Described by Simon Jenkins as 'one of Lutyens' most distinctive creations'. Extensive 20C wall-paintings by Walter Starmer, memorial to horses of WWI. Local archives display.
properties.name: St Jude on the Hill

properties.description: Small Grade I listed 12C chapel in lovely churchyard setting, it retains original architectural features and has interesting brasses, monuments and stained glass windows.
properties.name: St Mary the Virgin

properties.description: Classic Grade I listed Georgian church with outstanding interior and monuments. Renovated 2019/20.
properties.name: St Mary's Church, Battersea

properties.description: Modern architecture church with large copper and lead roof and concrete, brick and stained glass external structure. Marble, wood and plaster interior and artwork by Sculptor Freda Pinto and Gerald Holtom.
properties.name: St Paul's, Newington

properties.description: Britain's first co-partnership garden suburb, first houses built 1901. Parker and Unwin's plan introduced 1907, mainly Arts and Crafts style; fascinating social history.
properties.name: Brentham Garden Suburb

properties.description: Grade II Modernist House designed by German emigre architect Rudolf Frankel for his sister and family in 1938. The house remains relatively intact and retains the layout and original features which adhere to Modernist principles of the era.
properties.name: 1 Halsbury Close

properties.description: Tudor Manor House built for Sir William Compton in 1514, substantially altered in 17C, 18C & 19C. A museum since 1906 housing local history and community collections, archives, art & exhibitions of Bruce Castle, and Haringey area.
properties.name: Bruce Castle Museum

properties.description: London's story of an engineering family that changed the world. Dramatic new staircase below sculpture garden leads to underground chamber. Travel by train through first underwater shopping arcade & fairground to view Thames Tunnel portico.
properties.name: The Brunel Museum

properties.description: Grade ll* early 18C mansion.  Unique panelled dining room from the Chateau de Bercy, 18C Dutch wall paintings and  exquisite original plaster ceiling and Grade ll Temple shaped folly  by James 'Athenian' Stuart. .  Golf Club from 1894.ple s
properties.name: Camden Place (Chislehurst Golf Club)

properties.description: An 'Italian Romanesque' church set in Epping Forest, St Peter's was founded in 1840 and extended in 1887. The building underwent a major reordering throughout 2020 to save it from subsidence and create new community facilities.
properties.name: St Peter-in-the-Forest Church & Community Centre

properties.description: Grade I listed Norman brick-built church consisting of a nave and chancel. Tower at the west end. Gothic-style stone windows from the old church inserted into the present 1636 structure. Rare 17th Century glass was restored in 2020.
properties.name: St Lawrence Church, Morden

properties.description: Founded in 11C, with Jacobean memorial c1615. Burial site of 5 Archbishops of Canterbury.
properties.name: Church of St Mary the Blessed Virgin

properties.description: Four hexagon Modernist building within an Epping Forest setting. A sunny meeting room for Quaker worship faces a wooded burial ground of simple headstones, including those of Elizabeth Fry, William Mead, Guilielma Lister and Norman Frith.
properties.name: Quaker Meeting House, Wanstead

properties.description:
Built 1863 - a large corrugated iron chapel. Inside was transformed after the last war into a battleship by local sailors for Sea Cadets. 
It has decks, portholes a Bofors Gun and alter from the set of the 1964 film Becket.
properties.name: The Tin Tabernacle / Cambridge Hall

properties.description: The church (1822 - Grade I listed) is an early and important example of Greek Revival architecture in London. Significant features include the caryatids and tower copied from the Acropolis and the atmospheric crypt.
properties.name: St Pancras Church & Crypt

properties.description: Early 18C Grade II listed building incorporating plunge bath with Delft tiles, orangery, saloon and pump chamber with part-restored water wheel. Hermitage and sham bridge in grounds.
properties.name: Carshalton Water Tower and Historic Gardens

properties.description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's. NOTE: Closed on Monday 19 September
properties.name: UPDATED: City Information Centre

properties.description: New building as an urban accent - two independent houses atop each other. Contemporary in design it draws from the tectonic composition of adjacent Victorian houses. Features include rain water harvesting,  roof garden, solar water heating.
properties.name: 264 Westbourne Park Road

properties.description: Family home with a minimal carbon footprint on a very narrow site (8ft wide). Environmentally friendly house, utilising amongst many eco-friendly devices ground source heat pump heating & rainwater harvesting. RIBA Manser Medal Winner 2009.
properties.name: Gap House

properties.description: A development of residential and recreational moorings for historic vessels on the Thames. The unique Pier House, built to a high specification, provides a floating community centre just downstream from Tower Bridge.
properties.name: Hermitage Community Moorings

properties.description: Ruskinian walk from RIBA award-winning Chiswick Business Park, Gunnersbury Triangle Nature Reserve through South Acton Estate, birthplace of artist Patrick Caulfield; Woodlands Park Ice House; to home of Wm Willett, of Daylight Saving Time
properties.name: A Ruskinian Walk Through Shared Heritage

properties.description: Completed in 1895, Two Temple Place is a dazzling neo-Gothic gem on the Victoria Embankment, designed by gothic revivalist architect, John Loughborough Pearson, & commissioned by & built for William Waldorf Astor, as his estate office.
properties.name: Two Temple Place

properties.description: A public hall, theatre and gallery in grand Edwardian style. Grade II listed, Stanley made fun of the Victorian style with grand ornamentation. It reflects Stanley's interest in science, the arts and public cultural improvement.
properties.name: Stanley Arts

properties.description: Medieval Parish Church, 15C, enlarged & rebuilt in 19C. Shingle spire 1857, by Wollaston. Chancel by Ferrey, lengthened with East wall by Bodley & Garner. Scadbury Chapel (Walsingham tombs), with rood screen. Clock by Dent, 1858.
properties.name: St Nicholas Church, Chislehurst

properties.description: Designed by the world renowned Zaha Hadid Architects, Roca London Gallery is a unique space where water acts as the architectural theme. Guests can also visit 'Everything Flows', a major exhibition exploring the work of Zaha Hadid Design.
properties.name: Roca London Gallery

properties.description: Sensitive yet bold refurbishment of historic Grade II listed townhouse for The Wiener Library including dramatic first floor reading room, mezzanine and ground floor exhibition spaces.
properties.name: The Wiener Library

properties.description: One of London's most exciting creative spaces, Cody Dock provides a gateway to the Lea River Park and is home to a gallery, gardens, cafe & bar that make this the perfect pit stop for exploring The Line Sculpture trail and Lower Lea River.
properties.name: Cody Dock

properties.description: This guided walk around Clapham's Old Town features a radically redesigned public realm which changed the emphasis of the street environment to encourage people to walk and cycle instead of driving.
properties.name: Clapham Old Town and Venn Street

properties.description: Former Midland Grand Hotel, now St Pancras Renaissance Hotel and Chambers apartments. Includes hotel lobby and clock tower.
properties.name: St Pancras Chambers and Clock Tower

properties.description: The building features a limestone exterior designed to 'complement but not mimic' the surrounding historical architecture, whilst behind the façade is a 4-storey composition of steel, glass and exposed concrete.
properties.name: University of Greenwich, Stockwell Street

properties.description: Single-storey canal toll house (1911) where tolls were collected for passing through the lock. Grand Junction Canal connected the Thames at Brentford to the Industrial Midlands in 1794 at the height of the industrial revolution.
properties.name: Brentford Canal Toll House and Gauging Lock

properties.description: One of a pair of modern houses on a sensitive site in a conservation area. A triple-height staircase atrium brings light into the heart of the house and ground floor areas open onto courtyard gardens on three sides.
properties.name: Springbank

properties.description: A former Victorian workhouse that has been transformed through LB Camden's Community Investment Programme into a state of the art facility for 50 homeless people laid out around a beautiful suntrap courtyard.
properties.name: Mount Pleasant

properties.description: Loughborough Pearson's red brick building is unimposing from the outside, but inside is a riot of Gothic Revival design. Golden mosaics reveal the character of the Grade II* listed chapel, built as part of the Middlesex Hospital.
properties.name: Fitzrovia Chapel

properties.description: Tree-lined housing estate on the ridge of Central Hill & Crystal Palace, incorporating open spaces, views over London, gardens and sense of community. Rosemary Stjernstedt Ted Hollamby Adrian Sansom, Lambeth Borough Architects 1963.
properties.name: Central Hill Estate

properties.description: The operational factory of Kaymet, a maker of trays and trolleys since 1947. A hidden 1950s building with a small yard, originally a printing works. It is brick built, with clear-storey glazing and tubular truss north-light main shed roof.
properties.name: Kaymet Factory

properties.description: A BREEAM ‘Excellent’ high quality, contemporary and flexible office building with central atrium, exhibition space, restaurant, café, gym and terraces providing a dynamic and exciting workplace environment for staff and visitors.
properties.name: Subsea 7

properties.description: Two railway arches have been repurposed into a ceramic studio.
properties.name: Turning Earth Ceramics Hoxton - E2

properties.description: Ceramics centre for the Lee Valley, covering the entire top floor of an old hardware factory. Three rooms, providing just over 8000 sq ft of floor space; the main room is capped by its original saw-tooth glass roof feature.
properties.name: Turning Earth Ceramics Leyton - E10

properties.description:
Victorian Potting sheds converted to artists' studios set within the grounds of Grade II listed Cannizaro Park.
The eight resident artists will be displaying their work during the festival at these unique studios.
properties.name: Cannizaro Studios

properties.description: Grade II listed building dating back to 1270. Following the dissolution of Christ Church Priory in Orpington in the 1530s, the house became a rectory. Additions were built in 1959 to put in a library.
properties.name: The Priory, Orpington

properties.description: The town's oldest firm of funeral directors has conducted funerals from these premises since 1908. The original interior is Grade II listed. The building also contains the Frederick W Paine Museum and the firm's archive.
properties.name: Frederick W Paine Funeral Directors

properties.description: Built in 1923, to replace its 18C namesake, Grade ll listed Shrewsbury House is the focus of the Shrewsbury Park Estate conservation area, built 1934-1936 by John Laing and Sons. Two Civil Defence centres are within the grounds.
properties.name: Shrewsbury House

properties.description: Blackbook Winery is in a converted Victorian railway arch.  It is open plan, with all equipment required to process, ferment and age wine on site – press, tanks, barrels etc.  Our grapes come from English growers within 2 hours of London.
properties.name: Blackbook Winery

properties.description: An interlocking set of gallery spaces and archive across 5 floors of an old 3-storey 19C warehouse in a mews street in Bloomsbury. Its dark brick concealing a newly luminous interior carved out inside.
properties.name: The Perimeter

properties.description: The Small Beer Brewery was founded in 2017 by James Grundy and  Felix James. It is the first of its kind, specialising in brewing world class beer at a sociable strength.
properties.name: Small Beer Brewery

properties.description:
We are running our usual guided walking tours around historic Kingston this year with reduced numbers.

Our guided tours are informative, interesting and fun. For more information about us visit: https://www.kingstontourguides.org.uk/
properties.name: Kingston Historic walk

properties.description: James Maltby Bignall (1827-1885) worked in the practice of Sir George Gilbert Scott, the architect of St Pancras Station. The style of St Michael's is late Gothic Revival, in its size and height reminiscent of Northern European churches.
properties.name: St Michael and All Angels Church

properties.description: This house was built by its owners (2018-2022), which creates an acute sense of ownership and connection to the neighbourhood. It shows how small and redundant sites could be used to provide high quality and sustainable places to dwell.
properties.name: East House: The story of a self-built home in London

properties.description: Large, late 17C Grade II* listed house with fine staircase and Venetian window and Georgian additions, used as a family dwelling until the early 1900s. Reopened to the public in Feb 2009 following extensive restoration works.
properties.name: Valentines Mansion & Gardens

properties.description: Grade II* listed church dating from 12C with Medieval, Tudor, Georgian & Victorian features. 16C Tower. Church refurbishment and new extension in progress in 2022. Over 1300 monuments with four Grade II listed tombs in churchyard.
properties.name: St. Mary's Church, Walthamstow Village

properties.description: This transformation of a derelict pub into an architecture studio doubles up as a gallery and lecture theatre. The new office is an example of the practice’s approach towards existing structures and intelligent architectural interventions.
properties.name: Jonathan Tuckey Design Studio

properties.description: Crystal Palace Bowl is a South London icon: A venue of legends from Pink Floyd to Bob Marley, with a Stirling Prize nominated sculptural stage, revived from ruin by a local community campaign and ready to host the next generation of talent!
properties.name: Crystal Palace Bowl

properties.description: Originally St, Mary's Infants School, later as Holy Innocents' National School until 1934. It then became derelict until 1981 when it became headquarters of the Hornsey Historical Society in 1981 after refurbishment.
properties.name: The Old Schoolhouse

properties.description:
The Church was built in 1839/41 as a white 'Hall-Church'. 
The 1870s Gothic Revivalism was overseen to a very high standard, by James Brooks and helped by 10 top craftsmen of the day. We also have a WWI Memorial by Violet Pinwill.
properties.name: St Margaret's Church, Lee

properties.description: Unit used as an art studio in a small industrial estate.
properties.name: Cut Glass Studio Ltd, Tottenham Hale

properties.description: This flexible community space was constructed by self-build volunteers in 2019, making use of reclaimed materials. It offers a window onto the RUSS building site where 36 affordable, sustainable homes are being built for completion in 2023.
properties.name: Ladywell Self Build Community Hub

properties.description:
London is known for its rooftops. The Roof Garden at The Post Building has been designed as a one-off location for enjoyment, work and wellness looking out over some of its most memorable.

Open to the public 7 days a week!
properties.name: The Post Building

properties.description: The low carbon building is a straw bale construction built on compacted tyres with a cedar roof.  In the Perivale Nature Reserve owned by the Selborne Society it is used for society meeting and as an education centre for adults and schools.
properties.name: Bluebell Centre, Perivale Wood Nature Reserve

properties.description: Medieval style church rebuilt by Sir George Gilbert Scott after 1867 fire. Tower & south porch are 15C. Large nave with open timber-work roof leads to chancel dominated by superb stained glass window & rich alabaster reredos.
properties.name: Croydon Minster

properties.description: Terrace of five three-storey houses and a studio incorporating a sequence of communal and private spaces. Influential prototype for Camden social housing developments of the 1960s and 70s.
properties.name: Winscombe Street 1960s terrace

properties.description: The museum is situated in a shopfront in Leegate Shopping Centre, which has been described by the Evening Standard as "the worst shopping precinct in the country."
properties.name: Museum of Neoliberalism

properties.description: A radical transformation of an Edwardian Semi that has been completely opened up and renovated with bold materials and bright colours. A stage-set mountain is elevated on an exposed structure to form the striking rear extension.
properties.name: Mountain View House

properties.description: 1 Finsbury Avenue is a Grade II listed building constructed in the early 1980s by Arup Associates (Peter Foggo). As the first building in the Broadgate development it was significant in defining the speculative office typology in London.
properties.name: 1 Finsbury Avenue

properties.description: The Garden of Earthly Delights is a community garden and a "meanwhile" space to raise awareness of empty spaces in the city, grow food for the local community and increase biodiversity. We hold workshops and events to which all are welcome.
properties.name: GARDEN OF EARTHLY DELIGHTS🌱🐝🍅🦋

properties.description: Street Art and Murals can be found in many places across London. They are artistic expressions that can be challenging, thought provoking, funny or beautiful. We will explore the area of Brixton and see the art that celebrates a community.
properties.name: Local discoveries: Street Art in Brixton – a virtual tour with a London Blue Badge Tourist Guide

properties.description: A 4-mile outdoor walking tour taking in a variety of Wimbledon's greater and lesser known buildings, led by Ramblers group, the Metropolitan Walkers. Includes Wimbledon Village, and several buildings new to the tour this year.
properties.name: Wimbledon architecture walk

properties.description: Antepavilion Commission offers emerging architects and makers opportunities to create new work through hands-on construction. Works are put on temporary display in Columbia/ Brunswick Wharf, situated on the Regents Canal in Haggerston.
properties.name: Hoxton Docks

properties.description: A first of its kind global arts destination, Cromwell Place is located in five Grade II Listed townhouses in South Kensington. Home to some of the world’s most exciting rotating art exhibitors with a range in specialties.
properties.name: Cromwell Place

properties.description: This Victorian terraced house in South London, applies a questioning approach to produce an unconventional arrangement of interlocking geometric glass volumes which reveal a sequence of compelling interior spaces.
properties.name: Frame House

properties.description: Amongst the RIBA Stirling Prize shortlist 2022 sits Mæ Architect's Sands End Arts & Community scheme in Fulham. The centre consists of a single-storey building comprising bright, airy and flexible event spaces and a community café.
properties.name: Sands End Arts & Community Centre

properties.description: Remodelling and extension of rear of house to make a kitchen/diner/lounge with ancillary wc and utility spaces and a new small urban garden.
properties.name: Hedge Lane

properties.description: Early 20th C Grade II* listed church designed by CH Reilly. Byzantine in structure but prefiguring Modernism in its aesthetic, Nairn judged it “the best church of its date in London”, Reilly “the building I should like to be remembered by”.
properties.name: St Barnabas' Church and Mission Hall

properties.description: Wren designed building of 1675, interior lost in blitz of 1940, reopened 1957 with 'Wren inspired' interior
properties.name: St Bride's Church, Fleet Street

properties.description: This Grade I Mansion House, close to St Paul's Cathedral was designed by Edward Woodroofe in 1669 and completed in 1673.  The residence of successive Deans of St Pauls until the 1970's today it is the office to the Bishop of London
properties.name: The Old Deanery

properties.description:
Semi-detached residential 2-bed house totally refurbished by the owner-architect.
The main works included demolition of str. walls to achieve open plan living, new bathrooms, kitchen, porch, windows, green roof, UFH and insulation.
properties.name: 186A Uxbridge Road

properties.description: Architect Ana Sutherland will lead a guided tour of the Cator Estate, covering Eric Lyons' Span estates and unique modernist homes designed by architects Patrick Gwynne, Peter Moro and Walter Greaves.
properties.name: Modern Architecture in Blackheath walk

properties.description:
An industrial heritage site that was the hub of one of London’s first major pieces of urban infrastructure.
Its 18th and 19th century buildings will be restored by Tim Ronalds Architects to create the Quentin Blake Centre for Illustration.
properties.name: Quentin Blake Centre for Illustration - New River Head

properties.description:
Join us for an interesting and informative walk around Surbiton with our experienced guide. Find out why Surbiton was called the Queen of the suburbs and plenty more. 

Visit our website: https://www.kingstontourguides.org.uk/
properties.name: Surbiton Queen of the Suburbs

properties.description: Vanbrugh Park Estate was designed by Chamberlin, Powell and Bon. The estate shares many stylistic similarities with their wider work such as the semi-circular curved motifs, purposeful use of light, and approach to community living.
properties.name: Vanbrugh Park Estate

properties.description: An open and welcoming building, intent on fostering community. A rooftop basketball court crowns three storeys of studio space, all accessible via open-air staircases doubling as communal spaces.
properties.name: C1

properties.description: C3 is home to Bureau, a members club at the heart of Design District. Its undulating white facade creates informal pockets of space on the interior, ideal for flexible working models.
properties.name: C3 - Bureau

properties.description: A lower-ground level church space, originally a school-chapel. Stained glass windows (1820's) are from the original St. Mary Moorfields Church. 2 icons in contemporary Ethiopian-style depict Mary, Mother of the City & St. Joseph.
properties.name: St. Joseph's Church & Quiet Garden

properties.description: The Family Kitchen & Shop, Royal Botanic Gardens Kew, designed by architects HOK with front of house interiors by Mizzi Studio and Lumsden Design, is an environmentally driven, education-led food space for visitors of all ages.
properties.name: The Family Kitchen, Royal Botanic Gardens Kew

properties.description: A leisurely 19km cycle tour through back streets & quiet roads of Battersea, Stockwell and Vauxhall. Stopping to look & chat about a dozen fantastic unexpected artworks, statues and motifs in the public realm finishing at Southbank Waterloo
properties.name: After Colston & Gill - South West London statuary Cycle Tour

properties.description: A pre- 2nd WW - 1933 - now beautifully refurbished brick built sports pavilion surrounded by the fields of Tooting Common.
properties.name: Woodfield Pavilion

properties.description: This new sundial faces East so gets only morning sun. It is 10 m. square and was opened in 2021, and is publicly accessible 24/7
properties.name: Fleet Street heritage sundial

properties.description: Tour of the new Soho Photography Quarter and The Photographers’ Gallery's refurbished ground floor, which has been redesigned to connect to this new public space that features a 45m ‘Artfrieze’ at the core of a curated public art programme.
properties.name: Soho Photography Quarter

properties.description: Red brick and Portland stone corner building with three prominent signs in Arts & Craft style lettering in green and gold mosaic for the company 'TJ Boulting & Sons'.
properties.name: T J Boulting

properties.description: For NOW Gallery’s 2022 Art Commission JeeYoung Lee has created an environment inspired by memories, dreams, emotions, and her personal experience. The artist reinterprets her psychological landscape and thoughts into this environment.
properties.name: 'Maiden Voyage' by JeeYoung Lee

properties.description: A tour of one of the largest and best preserved early Victorian squares and gardens in London, also with a magnificent and original public library of 1906, which shows Byzantine and Art Nouveau influences, and a remarkable Gothic church.
properties.name: Thornhill Square

properties.description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm Closed Mon 19 September.
Combined guided tours of Amphitheatre and Guildhall Art Gallery at 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays.
The capital’s only known Roman Amphitheatre
properties.name: UPDATED: London's Roman Amphitheatre

properties.description: Our timber frame building was designed by Matrix Feminist Design Co-Operative, and built by women. It represents our community's history of activism-the same ethos that transformed our site from dereliction, into a thriving community garden
properties.name: Walworth Garden

properties.description:
A great little museum set in the Grade 2 listed Ossulston Estate - a prime example of pre-war Social housing - based on Karl Marz Hof in Vienna.
Open Wednesdays to Saturdays throughout Festival 
Sunday 11th Event
properties.name: People's Museum Somers Town

properties.description: Blenheim Gardens Estate was designed and built in the late 1960s - early 1970s by Lambeth’s Architecture Department under Ted Hollamby. It marks the shift from system-built high-rise towards communal and pedestrian-dominated spaces.
properties.name: Blenheim Gardens Estate

properties.description: Formerly known as East Ham Town Hall, is a magnificent municipal Grade II* listed building, with victorian red bricks and a clock tower. The building is still a working Town Hall with a variety of rooms available for hosting various events.
properties.name: East Ham Old Town Hall: Guided tour by a born & bread resident

properties.description: The Customer Service Centre & Library is a very modern civic, whilst being a natural fit with the neighbouring Edwardian buildings that front the busy Barking Road.
properties.name: East Ham Customer Service Centre and Library

properties.description: We will show how the long-distance trade with Canada  helped feed London’s growing population of 7 million people by 1910.  Our "museum without walls" will use virtual reality technology to to visualise historical connections.
properties.name: Millennium Mills: Feeding Edwardian London

properties.description: Hear about Brockley Conservation Area's unusually well preserved enclave of High Victorian and Edwardian domestic architecture from Brockley Society's historian Gillian Heywood MBE
properties.name: Brockley Conservation Area Historical Walk

properties.description: Two-Up Two-Down House is a reworking of a Victorian mid terrace by architects Khan Bonshek. They use imaginative spatial devices to maximise the limited floor area. Double height volumes & blurring of rooms combine to create space & light.
properties.name: Two-up Two-down House

properties.description:
The Passmore Edwards Library was opened in 1899. In its first year, the library registered over 3000 local bookworms.
The building has been used as a registry office before sitting dormant and is now open to the public as a creative hub.
properties.name: Applecart Arts: Exhibition of the building history, Ferha Farooqui's work and more

properties.description: The park opened in 1898. 7,000 attended the event, enjoying refreshments and speeches stressing the importance of creating resources for children. The walkways, fountain, bowling green, war memorial and cafe were incorporated over time.
properties.name: Central Park, War Memorial and Cafe

properties.description: This is an artist-run, community-focused space, that offers affordable studios since 2011. Built around 1893 and adjacent to Almshouses. Also, used as a bakery and later became laboratory glassware in the late 1950s.
properties.name: Red Door Studios: Family workshop, Exhibition featuring Ferha Farooqui's painting and more

properties.description: The Boleyn is a prominent landmark at a crossroads right by the former West Ham football ground. It is an exuberant piece of French-style Renaissance architecture built in 1899-1900 and reopened in June 2021 after a spectacular restoration.
properties.name: The Boleyn Tavern

properties.description: Open Studios, provides a unique glimpse to the architectural spaces and working studios of APT artists.  Over the weekend, there is also the opportunity to see our Group Show in the Gallery, curated by and featuring APT artist's work.
properties.name: Art in Perpetuity Trust

properties.description: A pavilion inspired by the organic shapes of nature and the transformational potential of seeds, currently hosting the exhibition "Saving Seed". The walls can rotate position allowing the space to perform like a seed cracking open.
properties.name: OmVed Gardens Chelsea Flower Show Pavilion

properties.description: Celebrate the Open House Festival with this fun and interactive walking tour about Britain's forgotten history of the Black Tudors. Learn how African and European alliances, wars and conquests shaped the journeys of four Black Tudors.
properties.name: The Mysterious Black Tudors - Riverside Walking Tour

properties.description: Tucked behind a busy road in W12, this former foundry is a multi-level development featuring an architects’ studio with courtyards and spaces for exhibitions and musical performances. The  building's 15m brick chimney is a local landmark.
properties.name: The Foundry

properties.description: Ever since the United States gained independence, Americans have been showing up again and again. This tour is about their influence on the UK from before the Revolutionary War to American heiresses marrying for titles to WWII to today.
properties.name: The American Other in London

properties.description: Home of the Worshipful Company of Saddlers, Saddlers’ Hall is built in a neo-classical style and impresses with bespoke period furniture, historical antiquities, and paintings. The highlight is the Great Hall.
properties.name: Saddlers' Hall

properties.description: As park of Queen's Park Day, this hour long stroll around Queen's Park will reveal its fascinating history, natural beauty and cultural inheritance
properties.name: Festival Walk in London's Queen's Park

properties.description: Part of a public realm enhancement project across London’s Royal Parks from 2017 to 2021, architecture and design practice Mizzi Studio saw the installation of a brass tubular food kiosk in St James' Park at the foot of Buckingham Palace.
properties.name: The Horseshoe Bend Kiosk, St James's Park, Near Buckingham Palace

properties.description:
The Serpentine Coffee House overlooking the Serpentine Lake designed by Mizzi Studio, with its undulating brass canopy roof that echoes a stingray’s flight through water,  has added a
new architectural landmark to London’s Hyde Park.
properties.name: The Serpentine Coffee House, The Royal Parks, Opposite The Serpentine Gallery

properties.description: The Migration Museum is located inside the Lewisham Shopping Centre.
properties.name: Migration Museum

properties.description: Start Stamford Brook tube. Follow the hidden river, Stamford Brook, through streets and parks.  Amongst the architecture we will see on this route is a delightful square with great variety   Finish near Hammersmith Station around 4 pm
properties.name: Stamford brook walk

properties.description: The former Alexandra Palace Railway Station now run by a charity for use by local people and organisations for classes, meetings and many other leisure activities.
properties.name: CUFOS - Community Use For the Old Station

properties.description:
Come and see our light filled space, green exterior and find out more about what we do at The Photography Foundation! 

Browse our mini exhibition & zines, and have your photo taken in our pop-up studio by one of our alumni.
properties.name: The Photography Foundation Open House (D2)

properties.description: The new ceramics studio occupies the top floor of a beautiful old saw-toothed factory building within the Crawley Road industrial estate, one of several new creative businesses joining the area
properties.name: Turning Earth Ceramics Haringey - N22

properties.description: Former indoor garden design workshop converted into a open-access ceramics studio.
properties.name: Turning Earth Ceramics Highgate - N6

properties.description: Visit New London Architecture's pop-up gallery at Westfield Stratford City to see the largest model of London. Celebrate the 10-year anniversary of the Games and learn more about the past and future of Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park.
properties.name: New London Architecture

properties.description: Discover the history of law and (dis)order in Covent Garden through the architecture of No. 28 Bow Street. This tour takes place outside and will focus on the external features of the former Bow Street Magistrates' Court and Police Station.
properties.name: Bow Street Police Museum

properties.description: An architect-led tour of the recent public realm improvements. The tour will also provide a chance to look inside the tap rooms, scooter shop and winery and speak to the makers, brewers and winemakers on the estate about their processes.
properties.name: Lockwood Way Industrial Estate - Architect-Led Tours

properties.description: The Copper Coffee House is a combination of neo-futuristic form and innovative use of copper that results in a functioning café that acts a work of public sculpture.
properties.name: Copper Coffee House

properties.description: The long terrace at 17a–79b Mansfield Road was the last part of the post-war Gospel Oak Redevelopment Area to be completed, and formed part of the London Borough of Camden’s ‘Golden Era’ of housing under borough architect Sydney Cook.
properties.name: 17a–79b Mansfield Road (access to two flats)

properties.description: A short introduction to the history of the docks and the impact maritime trade had on the cultural mix of people featuring the voices of locals including: Lascars, Ayahs, West Indians and Africans.
properties.name: Royal Docks walking tour

properties.description: A walk though White City exploring how its built environment has transformed multiple times in the past century and discussing what developers have emphasized and downplayed about the area's heritage to attract people to the area.
properties.name: A walk through the 'Great White City'

properties.description: Join Tim Peake on a discovery walk through time in the footsteps of the dockers and factory hands over what was once Thameside flood meadows and into the former industrial world of the Royal Docks now rapidly being repurposed.
properties.name: Time and tide waits for no man: a walk under, on and over water

properties.description: The tour charts the evolution of Covent Garden-incorporating the piazza, the wholesale produce market, social residential areas and supporting neighbourhoods - highlighting the social and commercial highs, lows and challenges.
properties.name: Fruit to Fashion: how a kitchen garden became a world famous piazza

properties.description:
A plain Victorian Church set in a wooded Churchyard, with a vibrant and striking set of Murals around the altar and the Choir. 
Has indoor toilet facilities. 
A good quality well used organ in good condition, and an excellent accoustic
properties.name: St Mary's Church Bromley

properties.description: This walk is a celebration of South Norwood’s history of invention and creativity. Learn about famous local, historic figures like inventor & industrialist William Stanley and the composer Samuel Coleridge Taylor as you explore the area.
properties.name: Inventions of South Norwood

properties.description: A walk along and around a stretch of London's most famous hidden river. The River Fleet is underground these days, but it's left its mark on the landscape. Discover the layers of history in this less explored corner of central London.
properties.name: The Fleet beneath your feet

properties.description: Celebrate the best writing about architects and the city at AHMM’s pop-up bookshop at Morag Myerscough’s Atoll. We’ve curated a special collection of books and maps by established publishers, smaller independents and Open City itself.
properties.name: Open Bookshop at 1 Finsbury Avenue

properties.description: We are opening the doors of our 3D Printing Studio at the Design District for all to experience the wonders of 3D printing. Come learn about this innovative technology, touch the materials, and see 3D printers in action!
properties.name: 3D Printing at Design District

properties.description: Wizard Works, London's cutest adventure bike bag brand, will be opening their studio in North Greenwich's Design District for a behind the scenes look at all things bag making.
properties.name: Wizard Works Open Studio

properties.description: A Grade II listed motor garage and petrol station built in the style of a Japanese pagoda in 1928. Now a Tesco Express.
properties.name: "Chinese" Garage

properties.description: Altab Ali Park was renamed in 1998 after a murdered 25-year-old Bangladeshi Sylheti clothing worker. Formerly known as St. Mary's Park, it is the site of the old 14 C white church, St. Mary Matfelon which gave Whitechapel its name.
properties.name: Altab Ali Park

properties.description: A revolutionary first-of-its-kind opening bridge. Powered by nothing but hand winches, this 12 tonne weathering steel and oak structure playfully rolls and inverts to allow boats to pass from river to dock.
properties.name: Rolling Bridge

properties.description: Wates Built 1960s Semi, extended & renovated into a vibrant, colourful stylish 21st Century home. Embracing Midcentury & Modern design with Bold Colours, Patterns & Materials to create the feeling of space, light & individuality throughout.
properties.name: LivingFunky House

properties.description:
Learn about architect Julian Sofaer and join in with activities related to our community garden.

Draw local endangered flowers: 
Sunday 3pm - 4pm

Learn about fruit & veg grown locally: 
Saturday 2.30pm - 4pm 
Sunday 1pm - 2.30pm
properties.name: Canal club community centre reopening party

properties.description: A pair of affordable studio buildings as part of a new creative district on the Greenwich peninsula. David Kohn Architects worked with developer Knight Dragon on two new build creative studio buildings as part of the Design District.
properties.name: A4 & B4: Design District

properties.description: Uncommon Projects moved into their new showroom in June 2022. The showroom will be open for walk in visitors for the duration of Open House.
properties.name: Uncommon Projects

properties.description: Visit our studio in David Kohn Architects' building A4 in Design District and see where we formulate and manufacture all of our products. Sample our full range and take part in a perfume oil making workshop.
properties.name: Homework Open Studio (A4)

properties.description: This mosque started as the adaptation of a terraced house a little further along Commercial Road back in the 1940s. It has since had a remarkable history that has seen it grow into one of the most significant Muslim institutions in the UK
properties.name: East London Mosque

properties.description: A rare surviving medieval church in The City of London. 2nd bomb of the Blitz hit it. Poet John Milton buried beneath the chancel step. Early Jewish graveyard. Beside the old London Wall. Shakespeare, Bunyan, Blake & Defoe all feature.
properties.name: St Giles’ Cripplegate

properties.description: Carved out of five historic military Grade II and II* listed buildings, Woolwich Works is a new cultural destination in London located in the royal Arsenal.
properties.name: Woolwich Works
